name: di-n-dodecyl sulfide
Reason: The molecule di-n-dodecyl sulfide consists of a sulfide functional group bonded to two long n-dodecyl chains. The longer carbon chain molecules generally have higher melting points due to increased van der Waals forces. However, flexibility and symmetry can also affect the melting point. The sulfide group itself contributes to the rigidity of the molecule but is not overly polar, thus having a balanced effect on the melting point. For the reference, n-dodecane has a melting point of -9.6. The addition of the sulfide between the two alkyl chains will increase the melting point. The joining of two n-dodecyl groups through a sulfide linkage is expected to significantly raise the melting point due to symmetry and increased molecular weight, while the non-polarity ensures the increase is not as dramatic as with polar groups. Each n-dodecyl chain's effect on the melting point can be considered as adding approximately 25 degrees to the melting point of n-dodecane. Since there are two chains, this will be doubled.
